    <Section Heading="The Problem: Too Many APIs, Too Much Friction" Level="4">
        <p>
            Imagine this: your team decides to add AI to your .NET application. You pick a model, wire up the HTTP client, handle the auth, parse the response schema—and it works. Then the product team asks to try a different model. Suddenly you have two HTTP clients, two authentication flows, two response formats, and twice the maintenance burden. Add a third model and things start to spiral.
        </p>
        <p>
            This is the reality that many .NET teams hit when integrating generative AI directly through vendor APIs. Each provider has its own conventions, and none of them speak fluent C#.
        </p>
        <CalloutBox Type="info" Title="Sound familiar?">
            <p>If you've ever copy-pasted an <code>HttpClient</code> setup just to talk to a different AI model, this article is for you.</p>
        </CalloutBox>
    </Section>

    <Section Heading="What is AWS Bedrock and Why Use It from .NET?" Level="4">
        <p>
            AWS Bedrock is Amazon's answer to the multi-model problem. It gives you a <b>single, consistent interface</b> to access foundation models from providers like Anthropic Claude and Amazon Titan—without juggling separate APIs, auth tokens, or request formats for each one.
        </p>
        <p>
            Think of Bedrock as a universal adapter—like those laptop power converters that work worldwide. You plug in once, and voltage, plug shape, and frequency differences disappear. Similarly, your .NET code plugs into Bedrock once, and differences between Claude, Titan, and other models are handled at the API layer.
        </p>
        <p>
            What makes it especially compelling for .NET developers is the official AWS SDK for .NET. You can invoke powerful AI models using idiomatic C# code, plugging straight into your existing projects—no context switching, no foreign tooling. Text generation, summarization, intelligent chat—all accessible through the same familiar patterns you already use for other AWS services.
        </p>

        <p>
            At a high level, every Bedrock request follows this flow:
        </p>

        <BlogImage ImagePath="/images/blog/ai/bedrock/bedrock-architecture-flow.svg" 
                   Description="Bedrock Request Flow: .NET App → Bedrock API → Model → Response" 
                   Number="1" />

        <Section Heading="How Bedrock Unifies Foundation Models" Level="5">
            <p>Here's what abstraction buys you when calling different models:</p>
            <table style="width:100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin-top: 1rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
                <tr style="background-color: #f5f5f5;">
                    <th style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px; text-align: left;"><b>Aspect</b></th>
                    <th style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px; text-align: left;"><b>Direct Claude API</b></th>
                    <th style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px; text-align: left;"><b>Direct Titan API</b></th>
                    <th style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px; text-align: left;"><b>Via Bedrock</b></th>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;">Authentication</td>
                    <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;">Custom API keys</td>
                    <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;">AWS credentials (different service)</td>
                    <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;">AWS IAM (unified)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;">Request Format</td>
                    <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;">Anthropic-specific JSON</td>
                    <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;">Amazon-specific JSON</td>
                    <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;">Bedrock abstracts API layer (formats vary slightly per model)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;">Error Handling</td>
                    <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;">Custom error codes &amp; retry logic</td>
                    <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;">Different error codes &amp; retry logic</td>
                    <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;">Consistent Bedrock exceptions</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;">Switching Models</td>
                    <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;">Rewrite auth + request logic</td>
                    <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;">Rewrite auth + request logic</td>
                    <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;">Often just change model ID (minor format tweaks may apply)</td>
                </tr>
            </table>
        </Section>
    </Section>

    <Section Heading="Why: The Need for Simplicity, Security, and Scale" Level="4">
        <ul>
            <li><b>Simplicity:</b> Less manual REST/API handling compared to direct integrations. The AWS SDK for .NET handles the heavy lifting so you can focus on building features.</li>
            <li><b>Security:</b> AWS IAM and credentials management give you enterprise-grade access control out of the box—no custom auth layers needed.</li>
            <li><b>Scale:</b> Bedrock is built for production, with built-in monitoring, throttling, and cost controls that would take weeks to build yourself.</li>
        </ul>
    </Section>

    <Section Heading="How: Step-by-Step Guide to Using AWS Bedrock from .NET" Level="4">
        <p>
            Now that you understand what Bedrock does and why it's valuable, let's get hands-on. In this section, we'll walk through setup, authentication, and basic model invocation. Then we'll explore how this scales in production systems.
        </p>
        <Section Heading="1. Prerequisites" Level="5">
            <ul>
                <li>An AWS account with Bedrock access enabled.</li>
                <li>AWS credentials with permissions for Bedrock (use <code>aws configure</code> for the shared credentials file).</li>
                <li>.NET 9 SDK or later installed.</li>
                <li>The following NuGet packages:
                    <ul>
                        <li>AWSSDK.Bedrock</li>
                        <li>AWSSDK.BedrockRuntime</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </Section>

        <Section Heading="2. Setting Up Your Project" Level="5">
            <p>You can use a simple C# script or a full .NET project. Here's how to reference the required libraries:</p>
            <CodeSnippet Language="csharp">
#r "nuget: AWSSDK.Bedrock, 3.7.0"
#r "nuget: AWSSDK.BedrockRuntime, 3.7.0"
            </CodeSnippet>
            <CalloutBox Type="tip" Title="For Standard .NET Projects">
                <p>If you're working in a regular .NET project (not a script), add the packages using the CLI:</p>
                <CodeSnippet Language="bash">
dotnet add package AWSSDK.Bedrock
dotnet add package AWSSDK.BedrockRuntime
                </CodeSnippet>
                <p>Or use the NuGet Package Manager in Visual Studio.</p>
            </CalloutBox>
        </Section>

        <Section Heading="3. Authenticating with AWS (Recommended)" Level="5">
            <p>
                The easiest and most secure way for most developers is to use the AWS shared credentials file. Run <code>aws configure</code> and the CLI will write your credentials to <code>~/.aws/credentials</code>. The AWS SDK for .NET automatically reads from this file—no extra code required.
            </p>
            <CodeSnippet Language="ini">
# ~/.aws/credentials
[default]
aws_access_key_id     = YOUR_ACCESS_KEY_ID
aws_secret_access_key = YOUR_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY
            </CodeSnippet>
            <p>To use the <code>default</code> profile, simply instantiate the client without passing credentials—the SDK picks it up automatically:</p>
            <CodeSnippet Language="csharp">
// SDK automatically resolves credentials from ~/.aws/credentials [default] profile
var bedrockClient = new AmazonBedrockClient(RegionEndpoint.USEast1);
            </CodeSnippet>
            <CalloutBox Type="tip" Title="Set Up in One Command">
                <p>Run <code>aws configure</code> and answer the prompts. The CLI writes the credentials file for you.</p>
            </CalloutBox>
            <CalloutBox Type="info" Title="Need advanced authentication or production setup?">
                <p>For IAM user credentials, EC2 instance roles, or troubleshooting, see <a href="/blog/ai/bedrock/advanced">the advanced article</a>.</p>
            </CalloutBox>
        </Section>

        <Section Heading="4. Common Setup Pitfalls & Solutions" Level="5">
            <p>Before diving into code, let's address the most common setup mistakes that catch developers:</p>
            <table style="width:100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin-top: 1rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
                <tr style="background-color: #f5f5f5;">
                    <th style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px; text-align: left;"><b>Step</b></th>
                    <th style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px; text-align: left;"><b>Common Error</b></th>
                    <th style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px; text-align: left;"><b>Fix</b></th>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;">AWS Configure</td>
                    <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;"><code>AmazonServiceException: Could not find credentials</code></td>
                    <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;">Verify credentials file exists at <code>~/.aws/credentials</code> (or <code>%USERPROFILE%\.aws\credentials</code> on Windows)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;">Enable Model Access</td>
                    <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;"><code>ResourceNotFoundException: Model not available</code></td>
                    <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;">Go to AWS Console → Bedrock → Model access and request access to the model (takes 5–15 min)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;">Region Mismatch</td>
                    <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;"><code>ModelNotFound exception</code></td>
                    <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;">Claude 3 Haiku is only in <code>us-east-1</code> and <code>us-west-2</code>. Verify your region matches model availability</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;">NuGet Version</td>
                    <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;">API method not found or signature mismatch</td>
                    <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;">Use AWSSDK.BedrockRuntime version 3.7.0 or later to match recent Bedrock API changes</td>
                </tr>
            </table>
            <CalloutBox Type="warning" Title="Region Availability Matters">
                <p>Not all models are available in all AWS regions. When you get a <code>ModelNotFound</code> exception, <b>check region first</b> before debugging your code. Use the AWS docs or Console to verify model availability in your target region.</p>
            </CalloutBox>
        </Section>

        <Section Heading="5. Quick Start: Your First Model Invocation" Level="5">
            <p>Now that everything is configured and common pitfalls are clear, let's invoke your first model. We'll show you how to list available models and then call Claude with a simple query.</p>

            <Section Heading="5a. List Available Foundation Models" Level="6">
                <p>Start by discovering what models Bedrock has available in your region:</p>
                <CodeSnippet Language="csharp" Number="3">
async Task ListAvailableModels(AmazonBedrockClient client)
{
    var request = new ListFoundationModelsRequest();
    var response = await client.ListFoundationModelsAsync(request);
    Console.WriteLine($"Found {response.ModelSummaries.Count} models:");
    foreach (var model in response.ModelSummaries.Take(10))
    {
        Console.WriteLine($"  Model ID: {model.ModelId}");
        Console.WriteLine($"  Name: {model.ModelName}");
        Console.WriteLine();
    }
}
                </CodeSnippet>
            </Section>

            <Section Heading="5b. InvokeModel vs. Converse API — Which Should You Use?" Level="5">
                <p>
                    Before invoking your first model, it's important to know that Bedrock exposes two different APIs for calling foundation models:
                </p>
                <table style="width:100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin-top: 1rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
                    <tr style="background-color: #f5f5f5;">
                        <th style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px; text-align: left;"><b>API</b></th>
                        <th style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px; text-align: left;"><b>Use Case</b></th>
                        <th style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px; text-align: left;"><b>Best For</b></th>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;"><code>InvokeModel</code></td>
                        <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;">Single request/response; full control over model parameters</td>
                        <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;">One-shot tasks, API customization, batch processing</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;"><code>Converse API</code> (newer)</td>
                        <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;">Multi-turn conversation; handles message history automatically</td>
                        <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;">Chatbots, ongoing conversations, abstracts provider differences</td>
                    </tr>
                </table>
                <p>
                    For this intro article, we'll focus on <code>InvokeModel</code> since it gives you lower-level control and is more common in production workflows. The Converse API is typically more convenient for chatbot scenarios but comes with less granular control.
                </p>
                <CalloutBox Type="tip" Title="Which API should I use?">
                    <p>Start with <code>InvokeModel</code> for control and transparency. If you find yourself managing conversation history manually, switching to <code>Converse API</code> can simplify things.</p>
                </CalloutBox>
            </Section>

            <Section Heading="5c. Invoking a Model (Anthropic Claude)" Level="5">
                <p>Now let's invoke Claude to get useful output. The <code>BedrockService</code> class wraps the Invoke API. Here is the core logic from <a href="https://github.com/ajaysskumar/ai-playground/blob/main/AwsBedrockExamples/Services/BedrockService.cs" target="_blank">BedrockService.cs</a>:</p>
                <CodeSnippet Language="csharp" Number="4">
public async Task&lt;string&gt; GetMovieDetails(string movieQuery)
{
    var prompt =
        $"\n\nHuman: You are a movie information expert. Provide detailed information about the movie '{movieQuery}'. " +
        "Return the results as a JSON array of objects with fields: title, year, category, directors, actors, plot, genre, rating. " +
        "If no movie is found, return an empty JSON array.\n\nAssistant:";

    var request = new InvokeModelRequest
    {
        ModelId = ModelId, // "anthropic.claude-3-haiku-20240307-v1:0"
        ContentType = "application/json",
        Accept = "application/json",
        Body = new System.IO.MemoryStream(System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(
            JsonSerializer.Serialize(new
            {
                anthropic_version = "bedrock-2023-05-31",
                max_tokens = 1024,
                messages = new[]
                {
                    new { role = "user", content = prompt }
                }
            })
        ))
    };

    var response = await _client.InvokeModelAsync(request);
    var responseBody = System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetString(response.Body.ToArray());
    return FormatJsonString(responseBody);
}
                </CodeSnippet>
                <p>
                    <b>What's happening:</b> You build an <code>InvokeModelRequest</code> with your prompt, serialize it as JSON, and send it to Bedrock. The response comes back as a stream; decode it to see Claude's answer.
                </p>
                <CalloutBox Type="tip" Title="Test Your Setup">
                    <p>Use this simple example to verify your credentials, region, and model access all work correctly before moving to production patterns.</p>
                </CalloutBox>
            </Section>
        </Section>

        <Section Heading="6. Production Patterns: Batch Processing & Error Recovery" Level="5">
            <p>
                Single queries are great for testing, but production systems need efficiency and resilience. Let's move beyond toy examples to a realistic scenario: <b>batch document summarization</b>. 
                Imagine your SaaS platform ingests customer support tickets and needs to auto-summarize them in real-time. With a naive approach, you'd loop through tickets one-by-one—slow and expensive. Here's a production-ready approach that batches requests and handles failures gracefully.
            </p>
            <CalloutBox Type="tip" Title="Why This Matters">
                <p>Bedrock pricing is per-request. A naive loop over 1000 tickets will cost significantly more than a batched approach with smart error recovery. Always design for batch efficiency in production.</p>
            </CalloutBox>

            <p><b>Compare these two approaches:</b></p>

            <CodeSnippet Language="csharp" Number="5" Description="❌ Naive approach: Sequential processing (slow and expensive)">
// Bad: loops sequentially, costs money, slow
foreach (var ticket in tickets)
{
    string summary = await service.GetMovieDetails(ticket.Description); // Slow!
    await db.SaveAsync(summary);
}
            </CodeSnippet>

            <CodeSnippet Language="csharp" Number="6" Description="✓ Production approach: Batched processing with error recovery">
public async Task&lt;List&lt;SummarizationResult&gt;&gt; BatchSummarizeTickets(List&lt;SupportTicket&gt; tickets)
{
    var results = new List&lt;SummarizationResult&gt;();
    var batchSize = 10; // Process in groups to avoid overwhelming Bedrock
    var results = new ConcurrentBag&lt;SummarizationResult&gt;();

    for (int i = 0; i &lt; tickets.Count; i += batchSize)
    {
        var batch = tickets.Skip(i).Take(batchSize).ToList();
        var tasks = batch.Select(async ticket =&gt;
        {
            try
            {
                var summary = await _bedrockService.SummarizeAsync(ticket.Description);
                results.Add(new SummarizationResult { TicketId = ticket.Id, Summary = summary, Success = true });
            }
            catch (ThrottlingException)
            {
                // Backoff and retry
                await Task.Delay(TimeSpan.FromMilliseconds(new Random().Next(100, 500)));
                results.Add(new SummarizationResult { TicketId = ticket.Id, ErrorMessage = "Rate limited", Success = false });
            }
            catch (Exception ex)
            {
                results.Add(new SummarizationResult { TicketId = ticket.Id, ErrorMessage = ex.Message, Success = false });
            }
        });
        await Task.WhenAll(tasks);
    }
    return results.OrderBy(r =&gt; r.TicketId).ToList();
}
            </CodeSnippet>

            <p>
                <b>Why batching?</b> By processing tickets in groups of 10 and using <code>Task.WhenAll</code>, you maximize throughput while respecting Bedrock's rate limits. Error handling ensures that throttling or transient failures don't crash your entire pipeline—each ticket is tracked independently.
            </p>

            <p><b>Example usage:</b></p>

            <CodeSnippet Language="csharp" Number="7">
var service = new BedrockService();
var tickets = new List&lt;SupportTicket&gt; { /* ... */ };
var results = await BatchSummarizeTickets(tickets);
var successCount = results.Count(r =&gt; r.Success);
Console.WriteLine($"Processed {results.Count} tickets, {successCount} succeeded");
            </CodeSnippet>

            <p><b>Key benefits of this approach:</b></p>
            <ul>
                <li><b>Batching:</b> Groups requests to balance throughput and cost</li>
                <li><b>Error Resilience:</b> Catches throttling and gracefully degrades</li>
                <li><b>Concurrent Processing:</b> <code>Task.WhenAll</code> processes multiple tickets in parallel (respecting throttle limits)</li>
                <li><b>Tracking:</b> Each result includes success/failure status for audit trails</li>
            </ul>

            <CalloutBox Type="tip" Title="Production Tip">
                <p>Store failed ticket IDs (from <code>Success == false</code>) in a retry queue. Set up a scheduled job to retry failed submissions with exponential backoff.</p>
            </CalloutBox>

            <CalloutBox Type="tip" Title="Full Example on GitHub">
                <p>See the complete <code>BedrockService</code> implementation including batching logic in the <a href="https://github.com/ajaysskumar/ai-playground/blob/main/AwsBedrockExamples/Services/BedrockService.cs" target="_blank">BedrockService.cs</a> file on GitHub.</p>
            </CalloutBox>
        </Section>
    </Section>

    <Section Heading="⚠️ Pitfalls to Avoid & Limitations to Know" Level="4">
        <p>
            Before shipping Bedrock to production, understand these real-world constraints. They won't stop you, but they will catch you off guard if you're unprepared.
        </p>

        <Section Heading="Regional Availability" Level="5">
            <p>
                Not all models are available in all AWS regions. Claude 3 Haiku and Sonnet are primarily in <code>us-east-1</code> and <code>us-west-2</code>. 
                Titan Text is available in more regions. Check the <a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/bedrock/latest/userguide/models-supported.html" target="_blank">AWS Bedrock documentation</a> 
                for the latest region matrix before deploying.
            </p>
            <CalloutBox Type="warning" Title="Real-world gotcha">
                <p><code>ModelNotFound</code> errors are almost always region mismatches, not code bugs. Save debugging time by verifying region first.</p>
            </CalloutBox>
        </Section>

        <Section Heading="Rate Limits & Quotas" Level="5">
            <p>
                Bedrock enforces account-specific quotas to protect infrastructure. The default is commonly around <b>100 requests per minute per model</b>, though this varies by region, account age, and model. 
                Exceed your quota and you'll get a <code>ThrottlingException</code>. In production, implement exponential backoff and request a higher quota from AWS Support if needed.
            </p>
            <CalloutBox Type="warning" Title="Quota varies by account">
                <p>Contact AWS Support to check your specific quota and request increases. Don't assume the 100 req/min default applies to your account.</p>
            </CalloutBox>
            <p><b>Pricing impact:</b> Bedrock charges per input + output token. A 1000-ticket batch can run approximately $5–20 depending on model and verbosity (check <a href="https://aws.amazon.com/bedrock/pricing/" target="_blank">current pricing</a> for exact rates). Always estimate costs before scaling.</p>
        </Section>

        <Section Heading="Model Differences Matter" Level="5">
            <p>
                Claude 3 models have different characteristics (approximate values—check <a href="https://aws.amazon.com/bedrock/pricing/" target="_blank">AWS pricing page</a> for current rates):
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li><b>Haiku (fastest, cheapest):</b> ~300ms latency, ~$0.25 per million input tokens. Best for simple tasks.</li>
                <li><b>Sonnet (balanced):</b> ~800ms latency, ~$3 per million input tokens. Best for complex reasoning.</li>
                <li><b>Token limits vary:</b> Check model docs for current context window and output limits.</li>
            </ul>
            <CalloutBox Type="tip" Title="Choose the right model">
                <p>Start with Haiku for testing. Switch to Sonnet only if you need better reasoning quality. Always benchmark latency + cost in your use case.</p>
            </CalloutBox>
        </Section>

        <Section Heading="Model Access Approval Delays" Level="5">
            <p>
                When you first try to use a model, Bedrock requires you to request access in the AWS Console. 
                This usually takes <b>5–15 minutes</b> but can be instant. Don't request access at 4:59 PM on Friday if you plan to demo on Monday.
            </p>
        </Section>

        <Section Heading="Common Errors & How to Fix Them" Level="5">
            <table style="width:100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin-top: 1rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
                <tr style="background-color: #f5f5f5;">
                    <th style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px; text-align: left;"><b>Error</b></th>
                    <th style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px; text-align: left;"><b>Cause</b></th>
                    <th style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px; text-align: left;"><b>Fix</b></th>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;"><code>ResourceNotFoundException</code></td>
                    <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;">Model not available or not enabled</td>
                    <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;">AWS Console → Bedrock → Model access. Request access and wait 5–15 min.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;"><code>ValidationException</code></td>
                    <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;">Malformed request (bad JSON structure)</td>
                    <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;">Verify your request JSON matches Bedrock's schema and <code>ContentType</code> is <code>application/json</code></td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;"><code>AccessDeniedException</code></td>
                    <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;">IAM permissions insufficient</td>
                    <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;">Verify your IAM user/role has <code>bedrock:InvokeModel</code> permissions</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;"><code>ThrottlingException</code></td>
                    <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;">Rate limit hit (100 req/min default)</td>
                    <td style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;">Implement exponential backoff. Request quota increase from AWS Support if you need higher throughput.</td>
                </tr>
            </table>
        </Section>
    </Section>

    <Section Heading="7. Summary" Level="4">
        <ul>
            <li><b>What:</b> AWS Bedrock is a managed service that abstracts vendor-specific AI APIs into a unified API interface (with C# SDK support).</li>
            <li><b>Why:</b> It reduces friction: unified auth (IAM), consistent error handling, and easy model switching.</li>
            <li><b>How:</b> Use <code>InvokeModel</code> for single requests, <code>Converse API</code> for multi-turn conversations. In production, always batch, handle throttling, and forecast costs.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
            This approach lets you build intelligent, generative features into your .NET apps with clarity and control. Whether you're prototyping or going to production, AWS Bedrock and .NET make GenAI accessible and robust.
        </p>

        <CalloutBox Type="tip" Title="💡 If You Remember Only One Thing">
            <p>
                <b>Bedrock = abstraction layer.</b> You control: the model you invoke, the prompt you send, and the cost/quality tradeoff. Start with <code>InvokeModel</code>, add error handling, batch in production, and always check region availability first when things break.
            </p>
        </CalloutBox>

